Marketing calculations are important to know what is working and what is not.
Below is a list of the top 10 most important formulas to help you evaluate 
the performance of your marketing 

1, CTR ( Click Through Rate )
(CLICKS ÷ IMPRESSIONS)× 100
clicks = number of times people clicked 
impression = number of time ad was shown 
How attractive is your ad? Out of everyone seen it, how many wanted to learn more?
High: the message resonates, the targeting is relevant, creative is strong
Low: poor targeting, weak creative, wrong audience, unclear value proposition, ad fatigue, bad headline
Top of the funnel metric
Good for A/B testing

Email = (EMAIL LINK CLICK ÷ EMAIL DELIVERED) × 100

2, CVR (Conversion Rate)
(CONVERSIONS ÷ CLICKS) × 100 
It measures the effectiveness of the landing page 
Conversion = Desired action taken
Visitors = people who landed on the landing page
Each step has its conversion rate (sign up, download lead magnet, checkout, purchase) 
Email sent - clicks- purchase

Funnel analysis to measure the CVR at each step of the funnel to see where people drop off 
CVR shows if the traffic is quality, high intent, the message resonates, and the ad  quality is good or not.


3, CPL (Cost per Lead) 
TOTAL AD SPENT ÷ TOTAL LEADS 

It tells whether lead generation is affordable. How much money do we spend to get one potential customer?
LEAD = request a demo, sign up, watch free webinar, and trials. 
Leads later converted through the sales team 

LEAD-TO-CONVERSION-RATE (NUMBER OF CUSTOMERS ÷ NUMBER OF LEADS) × 100
What percentage of the leads eventually became customers
Sometimes, high-quality but fewer leads generate more money

4, ROAS (Return on Ad Spend
REVENUE FROM ADS ÷ COST OF ADS 
Gross revenue generated for every dollar spent 
Sales driven by the ad campaign
It helps to decide 
- which campaign to scale 
- which one to stop
- where to allocate the budget

High ROAS does not mean profitable, as some high-ticket items might have low profit margin. Same for services. On long run, maintenance can outgrow the effort.

5, ROI (Return on Investment)
(( REVENUE-COST)÷ COST ) × 100
This accounts for profitability
It helps to evaluate the entire campaign, compare marketing channels, decide future budgets, reporting to management.
It is advisable to look at customer lifetime value how much more a customer generates over time.

6, CAC (CUSTOMER ACQUISITION COST)  
(TOTAL MARKETING + SALES EXPENSES) ÷ NUMBER OF NEW CUSTOMERS ACQUIRED 
It shows whether marketing efforts are profitable and sustainable in the long run. It helps with planning for long-term budgeting and growth 

7, Customer Lifetime Value (CLV)
(AVERAGE ORDER VALUE × PURCHASE FREQUENCY × AVERAGE CUSTOMER LIFESPAN 
How much a customer worth over time 

8, Cost per millie (CPM) 
(TOTAL COST ÷ TOTAL IMPRESSIONS) × 1000
It measures the cost of awareness 
It shows how effective brand awareness is 

9, Bounce Rate
  ( NUMBER OF SINGLE-PAGE VISIT ÷ TOTAL WEBSITE VISIT )× 100
It shows the effectiveness of the landing page, it can indicate ux, seo efforets, headlines, call to action, and traffic relevance 

10, Curn Rate 
The percentage of customers 
who stop using your services is mainly for subscription-based services. 
( NUMBER OF CUSTOMERS LOST ÷ TOTAL CUSTOMERS AT START OF PERIOD ) × 100

Show customer retention,
Directly affects growth
Helps identify product or service issues. 
Reasons ( poor experience, bad customer service, better competitor alternatives, price and value mismatch)



